{"slug": "diabolic", "root": "diabolic", "category": "quality", "gloss": "of the devil", "definition": "*Diabolic* means 'of the devil' — pertaining to Satan and his works, or to evil of a deliberate, malicious kind. In the history of magic it is the label that recast ordinary rites as demonic: a charm or cure becomes diabolic the moment authorities read a demon behind it.", "history": "From Greek *diabolos*, 'slanderer, accuser' (from *dia-*, 'across,' + *ballein*, 'to throw' — one who throws accusations), which named the Devil in Greek scripture; 'devil' is simply *diabolos* worn down. The Devil is, by his own title, the prosecutor. The word's decisive turn came in the later Middle Ages, when theologians and inquisitors folded folk magic, healing, and learned ritual into a single story of diabolical pact — the process, as the historian Michael Bailey traces it, of constructing witchcraft as an accusation. To call an act diabolic was less to describe it than to convict it.", "def_sources": [{"label": "David J. Collins, S.J. (ed.), The Sacred and the Sinister: Studies in Medieval Religion and Magic", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)", "url": "https://www.psupress.org/books/titles/978-0-271-08240-0.html", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "A collection of essays exploring how medieval people tried to draw a line between approved religious practice and forbidden magic — and how blurry and contested that line actually was in everyday life."}, {"label": "Kieckhefer, Magic in the Middle Ages", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)", "url": "https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/magic-in-the-middle-ages/8D2A1F278C9BCEE38BC3539821B838E8", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "A widely used introduction to what magic actually was in medieval Europe: who practiced it, what forms it took, and how it connected to religion, science, storytelling, and law. It also explains how fear of magic fed into the witch trials of later centuries."}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. diabolic (Greek diabolos)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "commentary": null, "commentary_sources": [], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Greek", "origin": "Greek diabolos 'slanderer, accuser' (dia- 'across' + ballein 'to throw')", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "The Devil is, by his own name, 'the one who throws accusations'; 'devil' is just diabolos worn down.", "hook": "The Devil is, literally, the prosecutor."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 1, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 1, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "name_match_count": 11, "by_variant": {"diabolical": 1}, "first_year": 2009, "colors": {"B": 8, "R": 2, "C": 2, "G": 1, "U": 2}, "by_year": {"2009": 1, "2010": 1, "2011": 1, "2012": 1, "2017": 2, "2018": 1, "2019": 1, "2022": 2, "2024": 2}}, "cards": [{"id": "5e2c1e0e-0a10-416a-9b50-96ee0cbbc24e", "name": "Hagra Diabolist", "set": "ZEN", "set_name": "Zendikar", "released": "2009-10-02", "type_line": "Creature — Ogre Shaman Ally", "rarity": "uncommon", "colors": ["B"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/c/3/c303e7e2-cb22-4dea-889f-d03e2494ed0f.jpg?1782715650", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/c/3/c303e7e2-cb22-4dea-889f-d03e2494ed0f.jpg?1782715650", "scryfall_uri": "https://scryfall.com/card/zen/95/hagra-diabolist?utm_source=api", "local": "img/diabolic/5e2c1e0e-0a10-416a-9b50-96ee0cbbc24e.jpg"}, {"id": "4fe9b57c-7743-46b5-b811-9766925e8bdf", "name": "Embrace My Diabolical Vision", "set": "OARC", "set_name": "Archenemy Schemes", "released": "2010-06-18", "type_line": "Scheme", "rarity": "common", "colors": [], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/4/8/48d8a236-4a89-43ed-8e2b-464770a474b0.jpg?1782753041", "img_normal": "https://cards.scryfall.io/normal/front/4/8/48d8a236-4a89-43ed-8e2b-464770a474b0.jpg?1782753041